WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.170 --> 00:00:02.363
- So, okay, let's get started.

00:00:03.770 --> 00:00:08.770
A question we frequently
come across is someone says

00:00:11.557 --> 00:00:14.480
"Well, I don't know about
X3 because I'm training

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:19.480
to fire, training to engage
my type two B fibers.

00:00:21.599 --> 00:00:25.020
I'm trying to get to a
certain type of fiber,

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:27.350
which I know I'm more predisposed."

00:00:27.350 --> 00:00:28.670
Like somebody who uses (murmur)

00:00:28.670 --> 00:00:30.680
they're like "I'm only
training my fast-twitch fibers

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:32.047
and my slow-twitch fibers."

00:00:34.350 --> 00:00:39.350
It amazes me that there
are still people believing

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:44.980
that you can train a certain fiber

00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:49.980
and not another certain fiber,
based on its fiber type.

00:00:50.330 --> 00:00:52.280
Now there is such a thing as fiber type,

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:55.223
and they do engage at different rates.

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:58.360
Now when I tell you the rates,

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:01.343
you'll understand how stupid
this line of thinking is.

00:01:04.015 --> 00:01:07.430
So, this is just from physiology text

00:01:07.430 --> 00:01:09.880
like, text, this has been
around since the 1970's

00:01:09.880 --> 00:01:11.100
and we've known this.

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:15.030
So, probably before most of you were born.

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:19.800
So slow-twitch fiber, which is type one,

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:24.800
engages in 100 milliseconds,
so way less than a second.

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:30.510
Type two A, fast-twitch,
the difference between

00:01:30.510 --> 00:01:33.000
slow and fast, 50 milliseconds,

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:34.920
so it fires twice as fast.

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:37.890
But that's in a window of time

00:01:37.890 --> 00:01:40.973
that is immeasurable by humans.

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:44.090
I mean, instruments can measure it, but

00:01:44.090 --> 00:01:46.410
you can't snap your
fingers 100 milliseconds

00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:47.963
or 50 milliseconds apart.

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:51.260
Then of course, type two B is very fast,

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:53.270
it's 25 milliseconds.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:58.270
So, the point is, you're engaging a muscle

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:02.413
when you exercise, when you
use extra or you lift weights,

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:08.050
and if you're contracting that muscle,

00:02:08.050 --> 00:02:10.080
and you're conscious of that contraction,

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:12.140
you're engaging everything.

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:17.140
And everything grows, when you stimulate,

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:20.823
when you take the musculature to fatigue.

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:25.190
Whether it's standard
training, obviously a greater

00:02:25.190 --> 00:02:26.980
level of fatigue with X3,

00:02:26.980 --> 00:02:31.040
greater level of growth with
X3, but you're fatiguing

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:33.640
all of these things, they're all firing,

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:35.930
it's the speed of activation,
that's the only thing.

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:40.930
So you can't really train
for a specific fiber type.

00:02:41.950 --> 00:02:45.990
So, it is information
that, while it exists,

00:02:45.990 --> 00:02:50.320
is highly meaningless to
you; therefore you should not

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:51.500
pay attention to it.

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:54.470
There are many more other
things that you should

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:57.370
pay attention to that are other than that.

00:02:57.370 --> 00:03:01.710
So that is today's Falsehood of Fitness,

